= Chapter 8: The Final Circuit
\
The giant Warden loomed like a mountain of corrupted stone. Every few seconds, its heavy chest would expand, and a sickening thum-thum would echo through the plaza, vibrating the loose wool fibers beneath Valen’s feet.

Valen and Master Elian crouched behind a pile of abandoned deepslate bricks, barely five blocks away from the master control panel. The panel was built into the base of the Grand Gateway, designed to cut the redstone power instantly in case of an emergency.

But there was a huge problem. The control housing was completely swallowed by a thick, pulsing knot of skulk. Dark blue tendrils had wrapped around the iron lever, pinning it firmly in the "ON" position.

"The skulk has locked the lever," Valen whispered, his voice a tiny thread of sound. "If I try to pry it open, the scraping sound will alert the Warden instantly."

Master Elian looked at the giant monster, then down at a heavy redstone clock mechanism he was holding. His old hands stopped trembling, replaced by a sudden, calm resolve.

"I will draw it away," Elian whispered softly.

"What? No, Master!" Valen gripped Elian's sleeve. "It’s too dangerous!"

"You are the one who understands the crystals, Valen. You have to save the city," Elian smiled gently, pushing a final roll of wool carpet into Valen's hands. "When you hear the distraction, clear that lever. Don't look back."

Before Valen could stop him, Master Elian stood up and sprinted away from the wool path, his hard leather boots striking the bare deepslate floor. TAP-TAP-TAP-TAP!

Instantly, the giant Warden’s antenna snapped straight up. It spun its massive body around with terrifying speed, letting out a deafening roar. It charged after the sound of Elian's footsteps, its massive stone arms swinging.

"Hey! Over here, you overgrown pile of cobblestone!" Elian yelled, throwing his redstone clock across the plaza. It landed near a row of houses, ticking loudly: Click-clack, click-clack!

The Warden smashed past the deepslate pillars, completely focused on the ticking machine.

"Now, Valen!" Elian’s voice echoed from the shadows.

Valen scrambled out from behind the bricks, throwing down his last blocks of wool to create a bridge straight to the control panel. He fell to his knees in front of the skulk-covered box.

He pulled out his iron apprentice knife. His hands shook as he shoved the blade into the slimy, velvet-blue moss, sawing frantically at the tendrils binding the lever.

The moment the blade cut into the skulk, a nearby Skulk Shrieker—hidden in the darkness beneath the gateway—began to spin. A horrible, ghostly scream pierced the air, and the sky above the plaza turned pitch-black, blinding Valen for a terrifying second.

The darkness effect! Valen thought in a panic, his vision swimming in shadows.

Across the plaza, the giant Warden stopped. It ignored the ticking clock. It knew the shrieker had found something. It turned around, its chest flaring with a brilliant, angry midnight-blue light.

"Come on, break!" Valen screamed in his mind, hacking at the final strand of skulk.

SNAP.

The tendril broke. Valen grabbed the heavy iron lever with both hands and slammed it down.

CLUNK!

The redstone lines beneath the plaza shattered their connections. The golden power lines running up the sides of the Grand Gateway instantly fizzled out. The roaring blue vortex inside the giant frame began to shrink, sputtering like a dying candle.

But the portal wasn't going down without a fight.

Deep within the shrinking vortex, a massive, shadowy silhouette slammed against the energy barrier from the other side. It was The Catalyst—the boss-level entity trapped in the Void Temple. It let out a sound that wasn't a roar, but a frequency so low it made the deepslate walls of Luminos-Vara begin to crack and crumble.

A massive surge of dark energy exploded outward from the dying portal. The shockwave hit Valen, throwing him backward off his wool path and onto the hard stone floor.

His golden tuning fork flew from his belt, clattering loudly against the cobblestone. PING-PING-PING-clatter!

Valen groaned, his vision slowly clearing from the darkness. He tried to stand, but his ankle twisted painfully. He looked up.

The Grand Gateway was finally dark. The portal was closed.

But the corruption had not stopped. The surge of dark energy had supercharged every piece of skulk in the plaza. And right in front of Valen, the giant, original Warden was standing. The closed portal hadn't shut it down. Instead, the final, loud ring of Valen's fallen tuning fork had locked the monster's attention directly onto him.

The Warden walked forward, its heavy footsteps shaking the dust from the ceiling, stepping off the skulk and coming to a halt right over the young apprentice.